---
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import PNotes from "../components/PNotes.astro";
import trueStory from "../img/true_story.png";
---

<p-slide class="center">
  <h2 class="main-gradient">But where did I actually use it?</h2>
  <Image
    src={trueStory}
    p-effect="from below"
    alt="It's a true story!"
    class="alter-image-size"
    style="--image-start-size: 7em"
  >
    A couple of real cases 👇
  </Image>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Time to get concrete. Here are two places where I actually put MCP to work
      — one you're looking at right now.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h2>🎤 <span class="main-gradient">These slides</span></h2>
  <ul class="more-margin">
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      Built on <a href="https://github.com/MaxArt2501/p-slides">p-slides</a> — the
      docs are the <span class="main-sub-gradient">MCP server</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      Ai queries layout classes, effects and fragment rules
      <span class="main-sub-gradient">before writing any code</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      Correct attribute form, right effect names,
      <span class="main-sub-gradient">no hallucinated APIs</span>
    </li>
  </ul>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      I fed the p-slides docs and custom-elements.json into an MCP server. AI
      then determined which layout class to use, whether to use the attribute or
      tag form for fragments, which effects exist. The result is code that
      actually works, first try.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>

<p-slide>
  <h2>🧩 <span class="main-gradient">Design system tooling</span></h2>
  <ul class="more-margin">
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from left">
      Each <span class="main-sub-gradient">Lit component</span> in the design system
      exposed as an MCP tool
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="zoom">
      Devs ask the AI: <em>"add a date picker with validation"</em> — it knows the
      <span class="main-sub-gradient">exact API</span>
    </li>
    <li p-fragment p-effect="from right">
      No more guessing props, slots, or events — the <span
        class="main-sub-gradient">docs are the context</span
      >
    </li>
  </ul>
  <PNotes>
    <p>
      Same idea applied internally: the design system component docs become an
      MCP server. AI assistants can suggest correct usage, right props, right
      events — without hallucinating component APIs that don't exist.
    </p>
  </PNotes>
</p-slide>
